<item rdf:about="http://use.perl.org/~brian_d_foy/journal/36942?from=rss">
<title>ActiveState's responds to 10 myths of open source</title>
<link>http://use.perl.org/~brian_d_foy/journal/36942?from=rss</link>
<description>&lt;p&gt;ActiveState has put together a free white paper on &lt;a href="http://www.activestate.com/business_solutions/ten_myths.pd"&gt;"10 Myths About Running Open Source Software in Your Business"&lt;/a&gt;. It's a fair look at open source for  the manager level.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;They don't come out as open source zealots. There are certainly some myths that come from both sides. The top three myths they address are:&lt;/p&gt;&lt;ul&gt;&lt;li&gt;You have to choose between Open Source Software and Propietary Software&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;Open Source Software is Free&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;Implementing Open Source Software is Only About Saving Money&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;p&gt;I like the last myth the best:&lt;/p&gt;&lt;ul&gt;&lt;li&gt;Your Business is not Running Open Source&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;</description>
<dc:creator>brian_d_foy</dc:creator>
<dc:date>2008-07-17T18:46:38+00:00</dc:date>
<dc:subject>journal</dc:subject>
</item>

<item rdf:about="http://use.perl.org/~brian_d_foy/journal/36935?from=rss">
<title>Bring your old O'Reilly shirts to OSCON</title>
<link>http://use.perl.org/~brian_d_foy/journal/36935?from=rss</link>
<description>&lt;p&gt;Marsee Henon from O'Reilly tells me that I could win a big prize if I bring the most old O'Reilly shirts to OSCON. They want to take a bunch of pictures of people wearing the previous versions of their shirts. There are prizes.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;The first 50 people wearing an O'Reilly shirt to show up at the O'Reilly booth get a prize too. I have no idea what the prize is, but I know there is a new Perl book out this month&lt;nobr&gt; &lt;wbr&gt;&lt;/nobr&gt;:)&lt;/p&gt;</description>
<dc:creator>brian_d_foy</dc:creator>
<dc:date>2008-07-16T22:22:12+00:00</dc:date>
<dc:subject>journal</dc:subject>
</item>

<item rdf:about="http://use.perl.org/~brian_d_foy/journal/36924?from=rss">
<title>Four master classes at YAPC::EU</title>
<link>http://use.perl.org/~brian_d_foy/journal/36924?from=rss</link>
<description>&lt;p&gt;Now that the &lt;a href="http://www.yapceurope2008.org/ye2008/purchase"&gt;YAPC::EU 2008&lt;/a&gt; website is live, you can register for the &lt;a href="http://www.yapceurope2008.org/ye2008/tutorials.html"&gt;master classes&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;This year there are 4 one-day classes. Two are before YAPC, and two are after YAPC. All classes are 900DKK (about $US190 or &amp;#8364;120) and run from 10:00 to 16:00.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Tuesday, August 12&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;ul&gt;&lt;li&gt;Test Automation with Perl - Gabor Szabo&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;Perl Teach In - Dave Cross&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Saturday, August 16&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;ul&gt;&lt;li&gt;Mastering Perl - brian d foy&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Saunday, August 17&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;ul&gt;&lt;li&gt;Practical Test Driven Development - Josh McAdams&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;p&gt;Master classes are low-cost classes taught by experienced instructors, and are primarily designed to make it possible for them to travel to the conference. Even if you don't want to take a class, tell a friend about them!&lt;/p&gt;</description>
<dc:creator>brian_d_foy</dc:creator>
<dc:date>2008-07-16T03:45:16+00:00</dc:date>
<dc:subject>journal</dc:subject>
</item>

<item rdf:about="http://use.perl.org/~brian_d_foy/journal/36883?from=rss">
<title>Win a Learning Perl, 5th Edition</title>
<link>http://use.perl.org/~brian_d_foy/journal/36883?from=rss</link>
<description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://oreilly.com/catalog/9780596520106/"&gt;Learning Perl, 5th Edition&lt;/a&gt; is here. I got five copies of it today, and apparently everyone lined up outside Amazon.com so now they are out-of-stock too. Luckily &lt;i&gt;Learning Perl&lt;/i&gt; came out a week before the iPhone otherwise people might be too busy to buy books.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Since I seem to have more copies than Amazon.com, I'll give one away before OSCON to someone who shows me that they want it the most. Use the criteria for my recent &lt;a href="http://use.perl.org/~brian_d_foy/journal/36778"&gt;OSCON pass give-away&lt;/a&gt; (won by Chris Dawson who took the time to make a video with his webcam). Although &lt;i&gt;Learning Perl&lt;/i&gt; isn't as costly as the OSCON registration, I'm still most impressed by people who are somehow clever in their attempt to convince me. This time, I might be partial to people trying to win the book to give as a gift.&lt;nobr&gt; &lt;wbr&gt;&lt;/nobr&gt;:)&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;I'll get it signed by all of the authors and ship it for free to anywhere the US Postal Service will send mail.  I can probably stuff a couple issues of &lt;a href="http://www.theperlreview.com/"&gt;The Perl Review&lt;/a&gt; in there too.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
<dc:creator>brian_d_foy</dc:creator>
<dc:date>2008-07-10T05:26:43+00:00</dc:date>
<dc:subject>journal</dc:subject>
</item>

